{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636173"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17567"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17567"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.16,0.04,0.36,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10257"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10257"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65407"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7187"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe medulla oblongata contains important nuclei and serves as an exit point for several cranial nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the exit point of the hypoglossal nerve from the medulla?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Between the pyramid and olive","Through the midline of the pyramid","Through the pre-olivary sulcus","Between the olive and inferior cerebellar peduncle","Through the post-olivary sulcus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve exits between the pyramid and olive\u003C/strong\u003E (Image) of the medulla through a series of rootlets. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pyramid and olive are parts of the medulla oblongata. The medulla oblongata makes up the lower part of the brainstem. The pyramid is a paired, ridge-like white matter structure located on the ventral surface of the medulla oblongata. and the olives are a pair of oval structures on either side of the pyramids. This location is consistent and helps identify this important motor nerve to the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrough the post-olivary sulcus\u003C/strong\u003E - This is where cranial nerves IX (glossopharyngeal) and X (vagus) exit\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrough the pre-olivary sulcus\u003C/strong\u003E - No cranial nerves exit through this sulcus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the olive and inferior cerebellar peduncle\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not an exit point for any cranial nerves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrough the midline of the pyramid\u003C/strong\u003E - The pyramids contain descending motor fibres and are not penetrated by cranial nerves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the exit points of cranial nerves from the brainstem is crucial for localising lesions and understanding the effects of various pathological processes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The hypoglossal nerve (cranial nerve XII) exits the medulla between the pyramid and olive.","The vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) exits the medulla in the post-olivary sulcus.","The glossopharyngeal nerve (cranial nerve IX) exits the medulla in the post-olivary sulcus superior to the vagus nerve."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cThe Cranial Nerves\u201d by OpenStax is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1320_The_Cranial_Nerves.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65407"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17567"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21342"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21342"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/oMCjQsddfO0xUzzNpPRPavtpz1lqpC.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/oMCjQsddfO0xUzzNpPRPavtpz1lqpC.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":401}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65407"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T17:13:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T17:13:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10257"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80130"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"upda